;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE config "Configuration and startup"
@{B}Configuration@{UB}

The configuration is kept in a plaintext file (MiniMail.config) located in the same drawer as the executable (MiniMail). @{" Here " link "configex"} is an example. If you want to, you can just modify the included file MiniMail.configex to suit your needs, and then rename it as MiniMail.config.

Each line consists of a @{" keyword " link configkey}, possibly followed by one or several arguments. Any number of spaces and/or tabs may be used to separate a keyword and its argument(s). Lines beginning with a semicolon (;) are assumed to be comments.


@{B}Startup@{UB}

To run MiniMail, either double click on its icon, or launch it from a Shell. No arguments can be passed through ToolTypes or Shell arguments at the moment.

If you want to, you can add a line to the end of your AmiTCP:bin/StartNet file, that launches MiniMail every time AmiTCP is started. Remember though, that if you move the program from its drawer, you have to move database and config files too!

Launching MiniMail from the WbStartup drawer on your harddrive is not recommended, as the database files and also some temporary files needed will be created within the WbStartup drawer!
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE configex "Configuration example"
mailserver	lls.se
autoival	90

username	volley
password	foobar
delmail		yes
allmail		yes

deffrom		volley@lls.se (Pelle Claesson)
deforganization	TheEnd Amiga

editor		CED %s -KEEPIO

pubscreen	Workbench
mainfont	newtopaz.font 8
listfont	newtopaz.font 8
headerfont	7a.font 8
bodyfont	7a.font 8

cx_popup	no
cx_hotkey	rawkey ramiga return
appicon		auto
appmenu		yes

timezone	+0100
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE configkey "Configuration keywords"
@{B}Configuration keywords@{UB}


@{B}Getting and sending mail@{UB}

@{I}mailserver <hostname>@{UI} - The mailserver to use. This is usually the last part of your email address; for example, my email address is volley@lls.se, and my mailserver is lls.se. If you're uncertain of what to put, please ask your internet provider!

@{I}autoival [<seconds>]@{UI} - MiniMail is capable of automatically looking for new mail at regular intervals. Autoival tells MiniMail how often, and if at all, these checks are to be made. If you want no automatic checks at all, just leave out the keyword.

@{I}username <username>@{UI} - Set this to your username, which is usually what you type in when your provider asks you for your "login". For example, my username is "volley". No default is provided.

@{I}password <password>@{UI} - A password is required in order to be able to get mail. It's generally the same as the password you're asked for after you send the provider your username (login). If you specify no password here, you'll be asked for one at the first getmail attempt.

@{I}allmail [yes|no]@{UI} - If enabled, MiniMail will get ALL mail from the server at each session (instead of only getting new mail). Useful together with delmail. The default is @{B}not@{UB} to get all mail.

@{I}delmail [yes|no]@{UI} - If enabled, MiniMail will try to delete all successfully retrieved mail from the server. The default is @{B}not@{UB} to delete mail.


@{B}Mail creation@{UB}

@{I}deffrom <from>@{UI} - This is the default from-field body, or in other words, your email address and real name. The suggested format is "my@email.adr (Real Name)" (not including the quotes). For example, I have "volley@lls.se (Pelle Claesson)" as deffrom. No default is provided.

@{I}defreplyto <reply-to>@{UI} - This is the default reply-to-field body. If you want replies to your mails to be sent to a different address than the one in the from-field, you can specify that here. Most people won't use this. No default.

@{I}deforganization <organization>@{UI} - If you're part of a specific group or organization, you can type it in here.

@{I}timezone (+|-)hh00@{UI} - This must be used if MiniMail can't obtain the correct timezone from your system. GMT is +0000 hours; if you live "west" of the GMT, specify a negative amount of hours, and if you live "east" of the GMT, specify a positive amount.

@{I}charset [<charset>]@{UI} - Let's you specify which charset to use when creating mail. The default is ISO-8859-1 (common in Europe). You might want to use for example US-ASCII, if you live in the States.


@{B}Look and feel@{UB}

@{I}editor <editor>@{UI} - MiniMail has no built-in text editor, and so, you have to specify a commandline for an external editor here. Replace the filename with %s (a percent sign followed by a lowercase s). Make sure the editor doesn't detach (for example, if you're using CygnusED, you would specify something like "ced %s -keepio"). No default. "ed %s" should work on most Amigas.

@{I}pubscreen <screenname>@{UI} - Specifies the name of the public screen to open on. Defaults to the default public screen. (Sorry, no customscreen support yet.)

@{I}window [left][/[top][/[width][/[height]]]]@{UI} - Lets you specify the initial dimensions of the main window. For example, window //320/100 will make it 320 pixels wide and 100 pixels tall. Defaults to the visible portion of the screen when first opened, then defaults to the dimensions the window had before it was last closed.

@{I}keepopen [yes|NO]@{UI} - If set to yes, the main window will be kept open while composing mails. Defaults to no (main window won't be kept open).

@{I}mainfont <fontname> <fontheight>@{UI} - Specifies the main font to use, for gadgets and the like. Proportional fonts are allowed. Defaults to the screen's font.

@{I}listfont <fontname> <fontheight>@{UI} - Specifies the font to use for the mail list. Proportional fonts are allowed. Defaults to the screen's font.

@{I}headerfont <fontname> <fontheight>@{UI} - Specifies the font to use for the mail header. Proportional fonts are allowed. Defaults to the screen's font.

@{I}bodyfont <fontname> <fontheight>@{UI} - Specifies the font to use for the mail body. Proportional fonts are allowed. Defaults to the screen's font.

@{I}cx_popup [yes|both|net|none]@{UI} - Determines if the main window, the net window, both of them, or none of them, are to be opened at startup. Defaults to yes, ie, the main window will be opened.

@{I}cx_hotkey <hotkey>@{UI} - The popup hotkey. Defaults to "rawkey ramiga return". Press it to open the main window.

@{I}appicon [yes|auto|no]@{UI} - Defines the operation of the AppIcon. Yes makes it permanent, no keeps it disabled at all times and auto makes it appear when the main window is iconified (and you can deiconify by doubleclicking on the icon).

@{I}appmenu [yes|auto|no]@{UI} - Defines the operation of the AppMenuItem. Yes makes it permanent, no keeps it disabled at all times while auto makes it appear only when the main window is iconified (and you can deiconify by selecting the menu item).
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE mainwindowl "The main window (list mode)"
@{B}The main window (list mode)@{UB}

The main window is always in one out of two modes: the list or @{" mails mode " link mainwindowm}.

In list mode, it consists of a list of mails, with one or several rows of gadgets at the top.


@{B}Gadgets@{UB}

@{I}Net..@{UI} - Brings up the @{" net window " link netwindow}.

@{I}Mails..@{UI} - Turns the window into @{" mails mode " link mainwindowm}.

@{I}New..@{UI} - Brings up the editor, letting you @{" compose a new mail " link compose}.

@{I}Inb@{UI} - Short for inbound. When selected, causes inbound mails to be shown in the list.

@{I}Outb@{UI} - Short for outbound. When selected, causes outbound mails to be shown in the list.

@{I}Hidden@{UI} - When selected, causes hidden mails to be shown too. If either Inb or Out is selected, only inbound and/or outbound hidden mails will be shown. If neither Inb nor Out is selected, only hidden mails are shown.

@{I}Hid@{UI} - Short for hide. Marks the currently selected mails as (un)hidden. Hidden mails are displayed in italics in the listview (please note that mails yet to be exported also are shown in italics).

@{I}Imp@{UI} - Short for important. Marks the currently selected mails as (un)important. Important mails are displayed with white foreground text.

@{I}Unr@{UI} - Short for unreplied. Marks the currently selected mails as (un)replied. All incoming mails are marked as unread. These are displayed in bold in the listview. After having been read once, the mail is marked as unreplied instead, causing it to be displayed in inverse mode.

@{I}Del@{UI} - Short for delete. By @{B}doubleclicking@{UB} on this gadget, the currently selected mails are deleted from the database.

@{I}Quit@{UI} - Click on this gadget to quit MiniMail.


@{B}Keyboard shortcuts@{UB}

@{I}ESC@{UI} - Hides the window.

@{I}Return@{UI} - Enters @{" mails mode " link mainwindowm}.


@{B}Menus@{UB}

@{I}Save to disk..@{UI} - A filerequester is brought up, letting you save the currently selected mail(s) to disk, in raw format (no formatting in the form of MIME decoding or similar is conducted).

@{I}Optimize..@{UI} - Initiates an optimization of the database. In other words, all deleted mails are removed from disk. Do this once in a while.

@{I}About..@{UI} - Brings up the about-requester.

@{I}Hide@{UI} - Hides the main window (same as using the close gadget or pressing the ESC key).

@{I}Quit@{UI} - Terminates MiniMail.
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE mainwindowm "The main window (mails mode)"
@{B}The main window (mails mode)@{UB}

The main window is always in one of two modes: mails mode or @{" list mode " link mainwindowl}.

In mails mode, it consists of a header section and a body section, as well as one or several rows of gadgets on top.


@{B}The header@{UB}

In the header section, information about the currently loaded mail is displayed.

@{I}From:@{UI} - Who sent the mail?

@{I}To:@{UI} - Who is the intended recipient?

@{I}Date:@{UI} - When was the mail was written?

@{I}Subj:@{UI} - The subject of the mail. Putting Re: (as in regarding) before the subject is a popular (and even compulsory) way of stating that this is a reply to some other mail. Forw: means it's a forward.

@{I}Nr:@{UI} - The internal mail number. The total number of mails is shown within parantheses. For example, "4 (6)" means this is mail 4 out of 6.

@{I}Status:@{UI} - The status of the current mail. Can be "Unread", "Unreplied" or "Unsent". An asterisk (*) means that the mail is marked as important, and an at-char (@) means it's marked as hidden.

@{I}Length:@{UI} - The length of the current mail in lines. The size in Kb is shown within parantheses. For example, "46 (5)" means this mail is 46 lines long, and about 5000 bytes large.


@{B}The body@{UB}

The body simply displays the body of the current mail, and optionally the header. If the mail consists of several parts, they are separated by lines shown in bold, containing the part number, the type, encoding scheme, and if available, name. To decode a binary part, click on the appropriate line. Signature separators (lines consisting of two dashes only (--)) are drawn as horizontal lines.


@{B}Gadgets@{UB}

@{I}Net..@{UI} - Brings up the @{" net window " link netwindow}.

@{I}List..@{UI} - Turns the window into @{" list mode " link mainwindowl}.

@{I}New..@{UI} - Brings up the editor, letting you @{" compose a new mail " link compose}.

@{I}Reply..@{UI} - Brings up the editor, letting you @{" reply to a mail " link reply}.

@{I}Forw..@{UI} - Brings up the editor, letting you @{" forward a mail " link forw}.

@{I}<@{UI} - Goes to the previous mail (or to the first one).

@{I}>@{UI} - Goes to the next mail (or to the last one).

@{I}>|@{UI} - Goes to the first unread mail (or to the last one).

@{I}Hid@{UI} - Short for hide. Marks the current mail as (un)hidden.

@{I}Imp@{UI} - Short for important. Marks the current mail as (un)important.

@{I}Unr@{UI} - Short for unreplied. Marks the current mail as (un)replied.

@{I}Del@{UI} - Short for delete. By @{B}doubleclicking@{UB} on this gadget, the current mail is deleted from the database, and the next one is loaded.

@{I}Hdr@{UI} - When selected, causes the actual header as present in the email to be displayed on top of the body.

@{I}Quit@{UI} - Click on this gadget to quit MiniMail.


@{B}Keyboard shortcuts@{UB}

@{I}ESC@{UI} - Hides the window.

@{I}Return@{UI} - Enters @{" mails mode " link mainwindowm}.

@{I}Cursor up/down@{UI} - Scrolls the mail down/up. Use with shift to scroll a whole page at a time.

@{I}Cursor left/right@{UI} - Goes to the previous/next mail. Use cursor right with shift to go to the next unread mail (or to the last one, if there're no unread ones).


@{B}Menus@{UB}

@{I}Save to disk..@{UI} - A filerequester is brought up, letting you save the current mail (as shown in the body section) to disk.

@{I}Optimize..@{UI} - Initiates an optimization of the database. In other words, all deleted mails are removed from disk. Do this once in a while.

@{I}About..@{UI} - Brings up the about-requester.

@{I}Hide@{UI} - Hides the main window (same as using the close gadget and pressing the ESC key).

@{I}Quit@{UI} - Terminates MiniMail.
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE netwindow "The net window"
@{B}The net window@{UB}

The net window can be opened from the main window by clicking on the "Net.." gadget.

It contains two gadgets, "Get mail" and "Put mail". By clicking on one of these, you either trigger the POP3-client (mail-getting part of MiniMail) or the SMTP-client (mail-putting part of MiniMail). Only one of the clients can run at a single time.

Next to the gadgets, the statuses of both clients are displayed.

Note that MiniMail can get mail automatically at regular intervals, and it will also try to put mail every once in a while, when there's mail to put. Therefore, there's usually no need to use any of these gadgets.


@{B}Keyboard shortcuts@{UB}

@{I}ESC@{UI} - Hides the window.

@{I}Return@{UI} - Triggers both the POP and SMTP clients.

@{I}Space@{UI} - Opens the main window and hides the net window.
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE compose "Composing a new mail"
@{B}Composing a new mail@{UB}

To send a new mail, click on "New.." in the main window. If everything has been set up correctly, the editor is loaded. If you have a signature file present (ProgDir:MiniMail.sig), it will be included in the mail.

After saving the text and quitting the editor, the @{" header window " link headerw} will be brought up. Please note that if you leave the editor without saving your text, MiniMail will assume that you cancelled the mail.
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE reply "Replying to a mail"
@{B}Replying to a mail@{UB}

If you want to reply to a mail you're reading, click on "Reply..". The editor will be loaded with a text containing a header, the original mail in quoted form and your signature.

After saving the text and quitting the editor, the @{" header window " link headerw} will be brought up. The From: field from the original message will be copied into the To: gadget. Also the Subject: field is copied.
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE forward "Forwarding a mail"
@{B}Forwarding a mail@{UB}

If you want to forward a mail you're reading to others, click on "Forward..". The editor will be loaded with a text containing containing a header, the original mail enclosed within begin/end lines, and your signature.

After saving the text and quitting the editor, the @{" header window " link headerw} will be brought up. The Subject: field is copied from the original mail.
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE headerw "The header window"
@{B}The header window@{UB}

The header window is used when you're composing a new mail, replying to a mail or forwarding a mail.

At the top, it contains two string gadgets, each with an accompanying button. The first string gadget is the "To:" gadget, in which you write down the email address(es) or the alias(es) of the intended recipient(s). If you have several recipients, separate them with commas. Use the button next to the string gadget to bring up the @{" from/to subwindow " link headerftw}. In the second string gadget, enter the subject of the message. The accompanying button can be used to bring up the @{" miscellaneous subwindow " link headermw}.

If you want to attach files to your message, click on the "Attachments.." gadget to go to the @{" attachments subwindow " link headeraw}. If you want to edit the text again, before proceeding, you can click on "Edit.." to bring up the editor again. When you're done, click on "Done" to store the mail. To cancel it, either close the window, or click on "Cancel". 

@{" The alias list " link userdb}
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE headerftw "The from/to subwindow"
@{B}The from/to subwindow@{UB}

The from/to subwindow lets you specify more specific information about the originator and destination of the mail. It contains six string gadgets.

@{I}From@{UI} - Specify who the letter is from here. Note that it's perfectly legal to enter for example a visiting friend's address and/or name here, as long as you enter your own address in the sender field. It is recommended to specify a default from-field in the config.

@{I}Sender@{UI} - Used to specify a sender, unless the from field above already contains the same information (which it usually does).

@{I}Reply-To@{UI} - Tells the receiver where to send replies to. Use with caution.

@{I}To@{UI} - Simply determines the primary recipient(s) of the mail. If you want to enter several recipients, separate them with commas.

@{I}Cc@{UI} - Secondary recipient(s), who are to be sent "carbon copies" of the mail.

@{I}Blind Cc@{UI} - Almost same as To and Cc, with the only exception that the receivers won't get to know about each other.

As you might expect, the "Done" gadget saves changes, while "Cancel" discards them.

@{" The alias list " link userdb}
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE headermw "The miscellaneous subwindow"
@{B}The from/to subwindow@{UB}

The miscellaneous subwindow lets you specify more specific information about the contents of the mail.

@{I}Subject@{UI} - Simply the subject of the mail. Please write something useful in here.

@{I}Keywords@{UI} - Keywords, separated by commas. (Rarely used feature.)

@{I}Comments@{UI} - Comments. (Rarely used feature.)

@{I}Organization@{UI} - Your group or organization.

The "Done" gadget saves changes, while "Cancel" discards them.

@{" The alias list " link userdb}
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE headeraw "The attachments subwindow"
@{B}The attachments subwindow@{UB}

The attachments subwindow lets you attach files to your mails.

Clicking on "Attach.." brings up a filerequester, that lets you select a file to add to the list. Several files can of course be attached, but make sure that it will be possible to hold the whole mail in memory. To remove a file from the list, select it and click "Detach". To detach all files, use "Detach all".

Surprise: click on the "Done" gadget when you're done. :)
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE userdb "The alias list"
@{B}The alias list@{UB}

The alias list feature can be used to set up a list of aliases, corresponding to one or several email addresses and/or aliases. @{" Here " link "userdbex"} is an example of an alias list.

Each line in the alias list file (ProgDir:MiniMail.aliases) begins with an alias, followed by one or several email addresses or aliases. This means that it's possible to create groups. (See the example.)

All aliases entered into any of the header window's To:, Cc: or Bcc: fields will be resolved as soon as you press enter, or just before the mail is sent.

(Note that for hysterical reasons, the file ProgDir:MiniMail.users will also be checked if ProgDir:MiniMail.aliases doesn't exist.)
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE userdbex "Alias list example"
volley		volley@lls.se (Pelle Claesson)
erik		e.andersson@lostander.gu.se
unts		unts@louder.bzmbzm.ch
theend		volley, erik, logog@worldmoc.hc
all		theend, unts
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE locale "Locale"
@{B}Locale@{UB}

MiniMail utilizes locale.library if running on AmigaOS release 38 or better. The built-in language is English. A Swedish catalog is included in the archive. If you want to create a catalog for your own language, or if you find errors in the ones included, please get in touch!
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE history "History"
@{B}History@{UB}

@{I}12.5.96@{UI} @{B}Version 1.3 is released, after LOADS of feedback!@{UB}

Changes from 1.2a to 1.3:
· Saved/ and Decoded/ directories included in archive  /Colin F. Thompson
· Password now asked for at first getmail attempt, if not in config  /Stefan Wegener
· The user database has been renamed, and is now known as the "alias list"  /Scott McMahan
· The standard output is now redirected, to ensure that error msgs will be visible
· Rewrites of some slow/bulky code, and some unused code has been commented out
· Now gives returncode 10 if startup fails
· Now doesn't get mail on startup, if no autoival was specified  /Erik Johansson
· Signature separator bars added <Erik Johansson>
· MIME part-texts are now quoted too
· Colons are no longer assumed to be quote chars
· Should now work on OS 2.04 (couldn't live without locale.library)  /Leo Anderson
· META characters (ĺ, ä, ö and so on) are now allowed in *all* fields  /several
· META characters correctly parsed when viewing a mail
· Finally: Correct scrolling in listviews!  /A340+Gavin Hamill
· Many speed optimizations, for example when loading a mail from list mode
· Save To Disk now works from lists mode even if no mail is loaded
· The hotkey for "Hdr" now flips the correct gadget  /Gavin Hamill
· Now clipping long maillines correctly when highlighting  /Gavin Hamill
· No longer linking with Amiga.lib
· All source recompiled with full optimization

@{I}6.5.96@{UI} @{B}Version 1.2a is released.@{UB}

Changes from 1.2 to 1.2a:
· Support for charsets added  /Harry J. Miktarian
· The version number in the X-Mailer field has been fixed (was 1.1 on 1.2)
· Minor fix in the "user database" handling (had problems with spaces)

@{I}28.4.96@{UI} @{B}Version 1.2 is released. First AmiNet release.@{UB}

Changes from 1.1 to 1.2:
· User database added  /Ein+volley
· "Ignore" gadget added to "MiniMail is already running" requester  /Ein+volley
· Size and progress indicators during getmail  /Ein+volley
· AppMenuItem support added  /Ein
· Number of mails added to "You have new mail" window  /Ein
· Crash-bug when deleting the last mail found and squashed  /Logixs, A.Ejdeling
· $VER: string added to executable  /Toaster
· Window locked during connection establishment and send operation  /volley
· "Continue" gadget added to optimize window  /Ein
· AppIcon position configurable  /Ein
· Quit-gadget added to main window  /Toaster+Ein
· Main window is activated when it's supposed to be brought up but already open  /Ein
· Major socket code cleanup (more reliable SMTP operation)
· Miscellaneous cosmetic fixes
· Can't scroll down past the end of an email in the main window any longer /A.Ejdeling
· Date-field parsing fixed (no more timezones like -10000 hours)
· Comments allowed in config file

@{I}11.3.96@{UI} @{B}Version 1.1 is released.@{UB}

@{" Early history " link history2}
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE history2 "Early history"
@{B}Early history@{UB}

@{I}21.11.95@{UI} Work begins on project Palantír, with the goal to create a mail/news system a lot better than the existing ones (see information on Palantír).

@{I}29.11.95@{UI} I decide to do the project as a "special project" at school.

@{I}21.12.95@{UI} After work on the msgbase, internal structures, GUIs, posts and so on, brainstorming leads to the conclusion that the project will grow too large (my 30 school hours dedicated to the project have been used up since long ago). The project is more or less split into two pieces - Palantír and MiniMail. MiniMail becomes the heavily reduced version of the so far nonexistant Palantír, limited to mail only, and with a very simple structure. New ideas will be added to the Palantír concept, while the work on MiniMail is finished off.

@{I}20.1.96@{UI} I now use MiniMail for reading and writing my own mail.

@{I}12.2.96@{UI} MiniMail ß is close to finished, only MIME base64 decoding and some cosmetic work remains. Work on this manual is initiated.

@{I}26.2.96@{UI} First ß is sent to Ein.

@{I}29.2.96@{UI} In one month, everything has to be finished. Urgh. :)
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE futureplans "Future plans"
@{B}Future plans@{UB}

There are no big future plans. I am thinking about implementing a postpone function as well as some kind of script support, but... no promises.

In any case, watch out for Palantír, which will hopefully supersede MiniMail soon. Please have a look at http://www.lls.se/~volley for more information!

MiniMail has no known bugs. :)
@ENDNODE

;***************************************************************************************************

@NODE author "About the author"
@{B}About the author@{UB}

I'm an 18 year old guy from Gothenburg, Sweden. I study nature science, hoping to continue with something more computer related after finishing highschool. I like playing volleyball, IRCing (look for me as volley!*volley@*.lls.se on #theend), and I just love trance/ambient music! Check out my homepage (http://www.lls.se/~volley) for a lot more info. =)

Anyway, whether it's about MiniMail or Palantír, or about something completely different (*winks* to those of you who know what that might be), feel free to write me at volley@lls.se.

By the way, English isn't my native language, so, if/when you find misspelled words and/or misformed sentences in this manual and/or in MiniMail, please let me know!

"People would never dream of doing the things they dream of doing" @{I}Me@{UI}

"There are temptations so immense, that it requires both strength and courage to give in to them" @{I}Oscar Wilde@{UI}
@ENDNODE

